Financial metrics temporarily unavailable (rate limited) - 2025-09-15

Title   : Kochi to host 5th World Teak Conference: Global meet on sustainable teak sector
Source  : www.thehindubusinessline.com
Published: 2025-09-15T05:27:52
Fetched : 2025-09-15T09:09:12.368710
URL     : https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/agri-business/kochi-to-host-5th-world-teak-conference-global-meet-on-sustainable-teak-sector/article70051445.ece
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Kochi will host the 5th World Teak Conference (WTC) from September 17 to 20 at the Grand Hyatt, bringing the global spotlight on sustainable teak forestry and trade. This is the first time India is hosting the event, which is expected to draw more than 350 delegates from 40 countries.
Themed “Sustainable Development of the Global Teak Sector – Adapting to Future Markets and Environments”, the conference will explore the challenges and opportunities facing the global teak industry, with discussions on socioeconomic trends, genetics, silviculture, technology, environment, and trade.
Jointly organised by the Kerala Forest Research Institute (KFRI) under KSCSTE, the Ministry of Environment, Forest and Climate Chang, TEAKNET, and the International Tropical Timber Organization (ITTO), Japan, with technical support from FAO, IUFRO, and MAFF Japan, the event will serve as a global platform for policymakers, researchers, traders, and farmers to shape the future of teak.
Kerala’s Nilambur: Heritage and future of teak forestry
Kannan C.S. Warrier, Director, KFRI, said: “Hosting the World Teak Conference in Kerala is a proud moment for India. With Nilambur being the cradle of teak plantations and home to the world’s first Teak Museum, Kerala represents both the heritage and the future of teak forestry. The conference will help chart sustainable pathways for the global teak sector while strengthening Kerala’s role as a knowledge hub.”
The four-day event will feature scientific sessions, B2B meetings, panel discussions, and field visits, making it a landmark gathering for the global teak community.
As a co-organiser, the International Tropical Timber Organization (ITTO) brings its longstanding expertise in tropical forest management, trade, and sustainable development to the conference. ITTO has supported numerous teak-related projects across producer countries and continues to play a central role in promoting sustainable practices that link local communities with global markets. Through this collaboration, ITTO aims to foster knowledge exchange and international cooperation, thereby strengthening the sustainability of the teak sector, said a press release.
Published on September 15, 2025

(skipped: outside allowed sources) Title: Launch of Securities Market Hackathon at Global Fintech Fest 2025 (GFF ’25)
URL     : https://www.sebi.gov.in/media-and-notifications/press-releases/jul-2025/launch-of-securities-market-hackathon-at-global-fintech-fest-2025-gff-25-_95410.html

Title   : Global central bank moves in focus as investors eye rate cuts 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-15T06:31:35
Fetched : 2025-09-15T09:09:12.368710
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/global-central-bank-moves-in-focus-as-investors-eye-rate-cuts/articleshow/123894196.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Market expert Rajeev Agrawal in an interview to ET Now noted that while the rate cut is largely expected, the flow of international capital remains uncertain.
“A 25 basis points cut is already pencilled in by everybody. It remains to be seen how the money moves back into the US market because clearly the international money has been holding off into moving into the US and it remains to be seen whether the markets become more attractive from that perspective. Clearly, the markets have run out and as we all know the S&P 500 in terms of the valuations is not necessarily cheap. So, really it is more of the trigger and how the US economy sort of gets a boost from a rate cut which will drive whether more money comes into the US markets.”
The global central banking calendar remains busy, with the Bank of England meeting scheduled for 18th September and the Bank of Japan addressing markets on 19th September. The bond market is already showing signs of excitement.
“The markets have pencilled in multiple rate cuts especially on the US side and now everybody is talking about three rate cuts in the next three meetings in 2025. And if that were to happen, then clearly the cost of capital comes down and as the cost of capital comes down, the equities start performing even better and that is again something once the expectations are set the valuations start sort of accordingly getting priced and that is what we are seeing. The expectation is there that there will be a cut on the Bank of England side and that will be possibly good for that economy. But we will see how the dynamics there are and if there is a rate cut across different countries, it will be ultimately good for the equity markets,” Agrawal explained.
Shifting focus to India, Agrawal shared his approach to domestic investments amidst recent economic developments. “No real consumption additions for the simple reason that consumption basket has already run up and it was always pricing in decent valuations already. So, really the way we are playing the consumption story and pretty much the improvement in the economy is through the financials and financials have a whole spectrum of companies, some price reasonably and others not so. So, we are more of the value guys and we tend towards companies which are much more reasonably priced.”
With multiple central banks expected to adjust rates and global investors watching closely, the interplay between policy moves, capital flows, and equity valuations is likely to dominate markets in the weeks ahead.
