Published on September 15, 2025

Title   : KRBL shares nosedive 13%. What’s behind the sharp selloff? 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-15T04:00:08
Fetched : 2025-09-15T10:02:17.554774
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/krbl-shares-in-focus-as-independent-director-quits-over-governance-concerns/articleshow/123891498.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
In a letter addressed to the board, Chaudhary said the current dynamics were inconsistent with the principles of effective governance and independent oversight, which are critical to safeguarding stakeholder interests.
He pointed to issues such as inconsistencies in recording minutes of meetings, withholding of information affecting decision-making, and the write-off of certain export receivables without adequate discussion.
Also read | Nifty can hit 28,500 in less than a year, says ICICI Securities; here’s why
He also raised questions over the use of CSR funds, the arbitrary distribution of variable pay and increments to those holding office or place of profit, significant changes to the company’s Object Clause without detailed deliberation, and undue interference by invitees in board and committee proceedings.
“In such an operating environment where dissent is suppressed or sidelined, remaining on the board would compromise both my professional ethics and obligations as defined under Indian corporate governance codes,” Chaudhary wrote, adding that he was unable to contribute meaningfully to the board’s functioning as envisaged under the regulatory framework for independent directors.
KRBL had disclosed Chaudhary’s resignation on September 9, but the details of his letter were made public only on Sunday.
The company's profit after tax (PAT) for the first quarter jumped 74% year-on-year (YoY) to Rs 151 crore, compared to Rs 87 crore in the same quarter of the previous fiscal, supported by robust revenue growth and improved operational performance. Sequentially, PAT was down 2% from Rs 154 crore in Q4FY25.
Revenue from operations rose 32% YoY to Rs 1,584 crore from Rs 1,199 crore, aided by strong demand in both domestic and export markets. On a quarter-on-quarter (QoQ) basis, it was higher by 10%.
Shares of KRBL ended 1% lower on Friday at Rs 443. The stock has risen over 70% in the last six months and about 45% year-to-date.
