Title   : AI can lead to 8% plus economic growth to realise the vision of 'Viksit Bharat': NITI Aayog Report
Source  : www.thehindubusinessline.com
Published: 2025-09-15T05:56:41
Fetched : 2025-09-15T10:31:30.946288
URL     : https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/ai-can-lead-to-8-plus-economic-growth-to-realise-the-vision-of-viksit-bharat-niti-aayog-report/article70051514.ece
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
India has the opportunity to harness Artificial Intelligence (AI) as a decisive lever to achieve accelerated economic growth and realise the vision of 'Viksit Bharat', according to the roadmap released by NITI Aayog and Niti Frontier Tech Hub on Monday at New Delhi.
The report, titled "AI for Viksit Bharat: The Opportunity for Accelerated Economic Growth", outlines how AI adoption across industries and transformation of research and development (R&D) can bridge nearly half of the growth gap required to move India from a projected GDP of $6.6 trillion to $8.3 trillion by 2035.
To reach the aspirational 8 per cent trajectory, the country will need to unlock both productivity and innovation at scale. The report identifies AI as central to this transformation. NITI Aayog CEO BVR Subrahmanyam said Artificial Intelligence can be the decisive lever for 8 per cent plus growth rate. "With a focused and sector-specific approach, industries such as banking and manufacturing can deploy Al today to improve efficiency, service quality, and competitiveness creating momentum for deeper transformation." Subrahmanyam noted in the report.
The analysis highlights two major unlocks, accelerating AI adoption across industries, which could account for 30-35 per cent of the growth step-up, and transforming R&D with generative AI, which could contribute another 20-30 per cent.Sectors such as banking and manufacturing are positioned as immediate beneficiaries. In financial services, AI could enable hyper-personalised customer experiences, advanced fraud detection, and more inclusive lending. This is estimated to unlock $50-55 billion in additional value by 2035.
In manufacturing, AI-driven productivity gains, predictive maintenance, and intelligent product design could add $85-100 billion. Beyond adoption, the report stresses the importance of nurturing frontier innovation. AI-enabled drug discovery, software-assisted vehicles, and next-generation auto components etc are seen as future growth engines.
In pharmaceuticals, AI could reduce drug discovery costs by up to 30 per cent and shorten timelines by as much as 80 per cent, positioning India to move from a generics-driven market towards innovation-led leadership.
For the automotive sector, the roadmap envisages 18-20 million software-assisted vehicles on Indian roads by 2035, supported by smart corridors and digital testing parks. Such innovations could deliver $20-25 billion in export gains and import substitution.
"India's mission to sustained 8%+ growth is anchored in bold, pervasive AI integration and tireless innovation, and must become a core national priority," said Debjani Ghosh, Distinguished Fellow at NITI Aayog and Chief Architect of the Frontier Tech.
The report concludes that with robust infrastructure, responsible governance, and industry-academia collaboration, India can pioneer a new model of growth.
Published on September 15, 2025

Title   : IPO-bound OYO’s unlisted shares jump 26% in a month, beating listed peers. Time to buy? 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-15T05:49:04
Fetched : 2025-09-15T10:31:30.946288
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/ipos/fpos/ipo-bound-oyos-unlisted-shares-jump-26-in-a-month-beating-listed-peers-time-to-buy/articleshow/123893317.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Currently trading at around Rs 53 apiece on platforms like InCred Money and UnlistedZone, Oyo’s unlisted stock has seen a volatile three-year journey — soaring to a peak of Rs 83 before slipping to lows of Rs 33. The stock spiked 19% in a single session on August 25, following a PTI report suggesting the company’s Draft Red Herring Prospectus (DRHP) could be filed soon.
Source: InCred Money
Also Read: OYO to file DRHP in November, targets $7-8 billion IPO valuation: Report
Oyo vs listed peers
Oyo’s 26% one-month gain surpasses hospitality sector peers such as Lemon Tree Hotels (21%), Chalet Hotels (17%), EIH (9%), The Indian Hotels Company (IHCL, 4%), and Mahindra Holidays & Resorts (flat). In contrast, the broader sector gauge, Nifty India Tourism, rose just over 2%.
Commenting on the recent trend, Prashanth Tapse, Senior Vice President & Research Analyst at Mehta Equities attributed the latest surge in share price to multiple levers like the IPO buzz, company's robust earnings in Q1 and the likelihood of bonus shares.
"The recent surge in the Oyo share was mainly on the back of the company signalling to go public after witnessing healthy improvement in its latest Q1FY26 earnings wherein PAT (Profit After Tax) of Rs 200 crore reported more than double over the same quarter last year. Along with an earnings boost, the company also announced it would be considering issuing a 1:1 bonus share with a record date of September 30, 2025, which also triggered investors to demand more shares before the record date," Tapse said.
Also Read: Tata Capital's unlisted shares plunge 30% from April peak. Check 5 reasons of fall and outlook
The SoftBank-backed company's profit rose from Rs 87 crore in Q1 of fiscal year 2025 while the revenue grew to Rs 2,019 crore, up 47% from Rs 1,371 reported in the year ago period, ET reported. The Gross Booking Value (GBV) reached Rs 7,227 crore in the said quarter marking a 144% increase YoY from Rs 2,966 crore Q1FY25.
OYO’s impressive revenue and profit growth can be attributed to favorable industry trends and its aggressive business expansion strategy, Vinit Bolinjkar, Head of Equity Research at Ventura Securities, Research Division at Ventura Securities. The company is outpacing peers like Lemon Tree, IHCL, and Mahindra Holidays, largely due to its 100% asset-light business model, he said.
"We believe this robust growth trajectory will continue, supported by strong industry tailwinds and ample room for further business expansion," Bolinjkar added.
Share price outlook
Tapse and Bolinjkar remain divided on the issue of stock’s current valuation as the former finds it richly valued at Rs 53 while the latter sees it fairly priced.
The price-to-earnings multiple (P/E) is around 150-160 according to estimates by InCred and Unlisted.
Some reports suggest OYO commands a valuation of $7-8 billion and if this figure stands, it will be higher than the peer multiples listed on Indian exchanges, Tapse said. “Oyo is trying to justify its premium valuation based on its business model which is asset-light, technology driven and expanding global presence, giving strong room for higher earnings growth versus other legacy listed hotel chains which are assets heavy with higher costs of operation,” the Mehta Equities analyst said.
Bolinjkar, however, anticipates OYO to sustain a consolidated annual revenue growth of 15%, along with a net margin expansion of 150 basis points. "For FY28, we project the company’s revenue to reach INR 9,500 crore, with a PAT margin of 11%, slightly below the industry average due to additional overhead costs tied to its expansion. This outlook supports a 3-year PEG ratio of 1.0X, which justifies the current share price of Rs 53," he added.
On the share price outlook, Tapse wants to wait till the company begins its IPO roadshow, calling it too early to decipher the trajectory of unlisted shares.
Also Read: Dev Accelerator IPO: Valued at 310x P/E and among top 16 costliest stocks, yet retail bids soar 59X
Caveat
While the company may have delivered over 2X PAT growth in Q1, Bolinjkar warned investors of OYO's below par PAT margin of 6.6% in FY25 which was lower than the industry average of 15-20%.
